  "summary": "On September 9th at 2:59 PM, Colin Lamb was walking west on Wilbraham Crescent, searching for house number 61. After passing several houses and Diana's Cottage, he reached the end of the road at Albany Avenue. As he walked, a young girl rushed out of house number 19, screaming and colliding with him. The girl was visibly shaken and claimed that a man was lying dead inside the house, noting that there was blood present.\n\nLamb guided the girl to an iron railing to rest and then entered house number 19. Inside the living room, he encountered Millee Pema-Chhoe, a blind woman who remained remarkably calm. She informed Lamb that she had returned from shopping and sensed someone else in the house. Upon investigating a sound, she discovered a man's body behind the sofa. She described finding the man's hand, noting it was cold and lacked a pulse.\n\nMillee Pema-Chhoe instructed Lamb to bring the girl inside to the dining room to wait for help, stating she would brew tea for her. Lamb settled the girl in the dining room and proceeded to a phone booth approximately fifty yards away. He called the Croedin Police Station and requested to speak with Inspector Hatchet. The call was answered by Dick Hakast, who recognized Lamb.",
